, MD','53','21','INDICATION: Status post trauma with headache, neck, face, back,\nand left knee pain with shortness of breath and dizziness.\n\nCOMPARISON: none\n\nTECHNIQUE: Noncontrast CT of the head with 5 mm images followed by\nan uncomplicated IV and oral contrast enhanced multi-slice CT\nacquisition of the cervical spine, thoracic spine, lumbar spine,\nchest, abdomen, and pelvis.  Sagittal and coronal reconstructions\nwere used to further delineate spine alignment.\n\nFINDINGS:\nHead: The ventricles and sulci are normal.   There are no\nextra-axial fluid collections.  There is no evidence of\nintraparenchymal hemorrhage, hydrocephalus or herniation.  There\nis no skull fracture or scalp swelling.\n\nFace: No acute fractures are seen.  Regional soft tissues are\nwithin normal limits.  There is complete opacification of the left\nmaxillary sinus with erosion of the medial maxillary wall.  There\nis a mucus retention cyst within the right maxillary sinus.  The\norbits are normal.  No intraconal or extraconal abnormalities are\nseen.  Multiple dental caries are seen with adjacent periapical\napices noted on the right side.\n\nCervical spine: Cervical spine is visualized from the skull base\nto the cervical thoracic junction.  There is no evidence of acute\nfracture or subluxation.  The prevertebral soft tissues are\nnormal.  The carotid and vertebral arteries demonstrate normal\ncontrast enhancement.  Coronal and sagittal reconstruction of the\ncervical spine shows straightening of the normal cervical\nlordosis.\n\nThoracic spine: There is no evidence of acute fracture or\nsubluxation.  The prevertebral soft tissues are normal.  The\ncarotid and vertebral arteries demonstrate normal contrast\nenhancement.  Coronal and sagittal reconstruction of the thoracic\nspine shows normal alignment.\n\nLumbar spine: There is no evidence of acute fracture or\nsubluxation.  The prevertebral soft tissues are normal.  The\ncarotid and vertebral arteries demonstrate normal contrast\nenhancement.  Coronal and sagittal reconstruction of the lumbar\nspine shows normal alignment.\n\nChest: The aorta and mediastinum are unremarkable.  The lungs are\nclear.  There is no pneumothorax.  The osseous structures are\nunremarkable.\n\nAbdomen: There is no free air or free fluid.  There is no evidence\nof acute solid or hollow organ injury.  The mesentery is normal.\n\nPelvis: There is no free air or free fluid.  The bowel and bladder\nare unremarkable.  There is no evidence of pelvic fracture.\n\n\n\nIMPRESSION:\n1.	No evidence of acute injury.\n2.	Left maxillary sinus and bilateral periodontal disease.\n\nI have personally reviewed the image(s) and this original or edited\nreport represents my interpretation.\n');
